Medical Termination of Pregnancy legislation for unharmful pregnancies up to 10 weeks.

Legislated Equal Pay on production of equal work.

Polygon and Medics findings from a 2009 analysis of primary health care services for poor women in South Africa show marked improvements in practice across all spheres of health care. The majority of recommendations are already within the realms of implementation except those with budgetary or labour implications where further those policy shifts from being permissive to obligatory will be necessary. Included in the recommendations below are those that in a far less strong formula are already in the drafting phase at Whitehall (e.g. appointing a responsible minister like Mr Mitchell metamorphosing into Whitehall establishing a clear line of responsibility to Mr Mitchell) or that have been the subject of discussion amongst BMA Medical Women’s Federation (MWF). The MWF however in addition are now committed to also take forward other issues like the time for parental leave (PL) calculation at present is to only include the maternity period and not PL for mothers and PL but none for fathers or mothers who opt for adoption.

The following requisite changes in the human rights of women in health care were included as the main report conclusions and recommendations of an investigative team of WMFs from across the world, Solidarity: a Comprehensive Package of Recommendations on Maternal and Women’s Rights in Health Care, available in Turkish, English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese and Italian.
